==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|pleden|lang=enm}}, {{term|plaiden|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|lang=fro|plaider||to plead, offer a plea}}, from {{term|lang=fro|plait}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{term|lang=la|placitum||a decree, sentence, suit, plea, etc.", in Classical {{etyl|la|en}}, "an opinion, determination, prescription, order; literally, that which is pleasing, pleasure}}, neuter of {{term|lang=la|placitus}}, past participle of {{term|lang=la|placere||to please}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈpliːd/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-plead.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|iːd|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|pleads|pleading|pled|past_qual=North America, Scotland|past2=pleaded|past2_qual=England}}

# To present an argument, especially in a legal case.
#: {{usex|The defendant has decided to '''plead''' not guilty.|lang=en}}
#* Bible, Job xvi. 21
#*: O that one might '''plead''' for a man with God, as a man pleadeth for his neighbour!
# To beg, beseech, or implore.
#: {{usex|He '''pleaded''' with me not to leave the house.|lang=en}}

